{
    "blocks": [
        {
            "id": "intro_raising",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Raising Errors",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Sometimes you want to **create your own errors** when something is wrong with the data or logic. This is called **raising an exception**."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Raising errors helps you catch problems early and communicate what went wrong."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "using_raise",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Using Raise",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Use the `raise` keyword followed by an error type and message."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "age = -5\n\nif age < 0:\n    raise ValueError(\"Age can't be negative\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "ValueError: Age can't be negative"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "When Python sees `raise`, it creates a `ValueError` with your custom message and stops execution. This tells the user exactly what went wrong."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "why_raise",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Why raise errors?** To stop bad data from causing bigger problems later in your program."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "def get_discount(price, percent):\n    if percent < 0 or percent > 100:\n        raise ValueError(\"Invalid percent\")\n    return price * (percent / 100)\n\nresult = get_discount(100, 20)\nprint(result)",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "20.0"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The function checks if `percent` is valid. If not, it raises an error immediately before doing any calculations."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_raise",
