                        "correctFeedback": "Perfect! ValueError is appropriate for invalid values.",
                        "incorrectFeedback": "Use ValueError for invalid values like empty strings.",
                        "explanation": "ValueError is used when the value doesn't meet requirements.",
                        "output": "Username: Alice"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "catching_raised_errors",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Errors you raise can be caught with try/except, just like built-in errors."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "def withdraw(balance, amount):\n    if amount > balance:\n        raise ValueError(\"Not enough funds\")\n    return balance - amount\n\ntry:\n    result = withdraw(100, 150)\nexcept ValueError as e:\n    print(f\"Error: {e}\")",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Error: Not enough funds"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The function raises a `ValueError` when amount exceeds balance. The try/except block catches it and prints a friendly message."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "quick_check_catching",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Can you catch errors that you raise with try/except?"
